I have to say, you do great marketing because I tried the IDE Cursor with very high expectations, but unfortunately, I was disappointed.

Large projects can hardly be opened, the editor freezes and crashes. I don’t have my usual VSCode UI, even though I transferred the settings exactly. 

And then the shortcuts were also overwritten. I realized how often I use certain shortcuts that didn’t work within Cursor (for example, Command+Shift+K to delete a line, since Cursor wants to use CMD+K for itself, which I find a very bad idea). 

Eventually, the versioning system Git stopped working and didn’t recognize the changes anymore. 

All in all, I can say that maybe it’s good for a simple, basic project. Ours was a huge NxMonoRepo with many different applications, and Cursor couldn’t handle it at all. 

I tried it for a few days, then switched back to VSCode. Sorry.

Chat only has access to relevant snippets from a database of embeddings

Even though I specified the /app folder in the inline context, it is still clueless.  So with frustration, I made it as CLEAR as humanly possible with "I have used the "@app" context each time to specify ALL files within the /app folder.  Since that doesn't seem to work, give me a list of all FontAwesome icons being used in all PHP files within the /app folder." to which it again replied:

"I understand now that you're referring to the /app folder.

Unfortunately, I still can't provide a list of all FontAwesome icons being used in all PHP files within the /app folder. The reason is that I don't have any PHP code snippets in my context, and the provided CSS code snippets don't contain any references to FontAwesome icons.

To help me better, could you please provide some PHP code snippets from the /app folder that use FontAwesome icons? Alternatively, you can also try searching for the fa- class or FontAwesome references in your PHP files within the /app folder."

I am at a **LOSS**.  Is Codeium simply NOT codebase/application context aware whatsoever??  Does it ONLY work with tiny "snippets"?  I feel like this is a SIMPLE question for a "modern coding superpower" AI. 🤔

**Thanks!**

**Example #2** - I told it to "Give me a list of all FontAwesome icons used throughout the entire application.", and it responded with:

"I don't have enough information to provide a list of all FontAwesome icons used throughout the entire application. The provided code snippets only contain CSS styles for Tailwind theme, but do not include any HTML or JavaScript code that would use FontAwesome icons.

If you can provide more context or code snippets that include the usage of FontAwesome icons, I would be happy to help you identify the icons used. Alternatively, you can also try searching for the fa- class in your codebase, which is a common prefix for FontAwesome icons.".

When I click on [Advanced] I see the required application folder listed under "Pinned Contexts" where I added it immediately after installing the plugin, as well as a green dot next to the "Local Indexes".  So I tried using the inline context feature with "@app Give me a list of all FontAwesome icons being used." to which it replied:

"I have access to your codebase, but I need more clarity on what directory, file, or feature of the codebase you're asking about. Could you please specify which part of the application you're referring to? For example, is it a specific React component, a Vue.js file, or a HTML template?

If you can provide more context or point me to a specific directory or file, I can try to scan the code and provide a list of FontAwesome icons being used."

If you say things like "Can you update this file" it'll respond with "Yes I can, here are the edits you can apply" .. as opposed to "Make the updates to this file". As to why it says it can't access your files, because the underlying LLM is built on rules that tell it that it doesn't have file access. It's Cursor that gives it file access and tell it it has file access, but that's a later-rule so sometimes the original older rules come through.
